I. STATEMENT OF ISSUES PRESENTED

1. Whether an ex parte order suspending parenting time is void where it was entered without a verified pleading or affidavit showing immediate and irreparable harm as required by MCR 3.207(B).

Answer: Yes. The order is procedurally defective and void.

2. Whether continued suspension of parenting time for 192+ days without clear and convincing evidence of endangerment violates Michigan's statutory presumption in favor of parenting time under MCL 722.27a.

Answer: Yes. The suspension violates the statutory presumption and exceeds permissible judicial discretion.

3. Whether suspension of a father's parenting time for 192+ days without proper notice, hearing, or findings violates his Fourteenth Amendment due process rights in the parent-child relationship.

Answer: Yes. The deprivation violates fundamental constitutional protections.

4. Whether immediate restoration of parenting time is required where a six-year-old child has been completely separated from his father for 192+ consecutive days during a critical developmental period.

Answer: Yes. Every additional day causes irreparable harm requiring emergency relief.

II. STATEMENT OF FACTS

A. Background and Established Parenting Time

Andrew Pigors is the biological father of Lincoln Watson Pigors (DOB: June 27, 2018), now age six. For years, Mr. Pigors exercised substantial parenting time, including a 50/50 custody arrangement providing 182.5 overnights per year.

Following a custody trial on July 17, 2024, this Court reduced Mr. Pigors' parenting time to 79 overnights per year (approximately 32% of the year). While Mr. Pigors believes this reduction was error—and has preserved appellate rights on that issue—he complied with all terms of the July 17, 2024 order.

During the period from July 2024 through July 2025, no incidents of abuse, neglect, or danger occurred during Mr. Pigors' parenting time. Lincoln was healthy, safe, and developing normally in his father's care.

B. The August 8, 2025 Ex Parte Suspension

On or about August 8, 2025, this Court entered an order suspending Mr. Pigors' parenting time entirely. The order was entered ex parte—without notice to Mr. Pigors and without opportunity for him to be heard.

The record contains no verified pleading or affidavit supporting the order. The order contains no written findings explaining what immediate and irreparable harm necessitated deprivation of Mr. Pigors' parental rights without due process. The order contains no time limitation and no mechanism for Mr. Pigors to seek prompt review.

The order violated MCR 3.207(B), which explicitly requires ex parte relief to be supported by "specific facts shown by affidavit or by a verified pleading" demonstrating "immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage will result to the moving party before the adverse party or the adverse party's attorney can be heard in opposition."

The order also violated MCL 722.27a(3), which requires "clear and convincing evidence" before a court may deny parenting time based on endangerment.

C. Improper Continuation Without Findings

The August 8, 2025 suspension was continued at subsequent hearings on September 4, 2025, October 29, 2025, and November 26, 2025. Additional hearings have occurred or are scheduled.

At each hearing, the suspension was continued without the Court making the statutorily required findings under MCL 722.27a(3) that parenting time would endanger Lincoln's physical, mental, moral, or emotional health.

Mr. Pigors has been denied meaningful opportunity to present evidence contradicting Ms. Watson's allegations. When Mr. Pigors has attempted to file motions or present evidence, he has faced procedural barriers and sanctions.

As of the filing of this motion, Lincoln has been completely deprived of contact with his father for ONE HUNDRED NINETY-TWO (192) consecutive days. This represents more than six months of separation during a critical developmental period in Lincoln's young life.

D. The Record Evidence Contradicts Suspension

The objective evidence in the record overwhelmingly contradicts any basis for suspending Mr. Pigors' parenting time:

1. HealthWest Evaluation (Court-Ordered)

At this Court's direction, Mr. Pigors completed a comprehensive mental health evaluation conducted by HealthWest. The evaluation consisted of 82 pages of reports, assessments, testing, and clinical observations.

The HealthWest evaluation found:
• NO evidence Mr. Pigors poses danger to Lincoln
• NO significant mental health concerns that would impair parenting
• Recommendation for substantial parenting time with Lincoln
• Observations that Mr. Pigors demonstrates appropriate parenting skills

The HealthWest evaluation directly contradicts Ms. Watson's allegations and supports restoration of parenting time.

2. Medical Records

Mr. Pigors has obtained and reviewed Lincoln's medical records. The records contain:
• NO evidence of injuries during Mr. Pigors' parenting time
• NO reports from medical providers of suspected abuse or neglect
• NO findings consistent with Ms. Watson's allegation of "arsenic poisoning"
• NO emergency room visits or toxicology tests
• NO documentation supporting Ms. Watson's claims of danger

3. Police Reports

Mr. Pigors has obtained relevant police reports. The reports contain:
• NO arrests or criminal charges against Mr. Pigors for domestic violence
• NO substantiated allegations of assault or physical violence
• NO evidence corroborating Ms. Watson's claims
• Documentation showing Mr. Pigors cooperated with law enforcement

4. The "Second Evaluation" Is Not In Evidence

This Court has referenced a "second mental health evaluation" as a basis for suspending parenting time. However:
• Mr. Pigors never completed a "second evaluation"
• No expert has testified regarding any such evaluation
• No evaluation report has been authenticated under MRE 901
• No foundation has been established for reliability under MRE 702-703
• The Court excluded the favorable HealthWest evaluation Mr. Pigors did complete

The reliance on an unauthenticated, unsubstantiated "second evaluation" while excluding the authenticated HealthWest evaluation violates basic evidence rules and due process.

E. Pattern of False Allegations by Defendant

Ms. Watson has made multiple demonstrably false allegations against Mr. Pigors:

1. Arsenic Poisoning: Ms. Watson alleged Mr. Pigors poisoned her with arsenic. Medical records contain zero evidence of poisoning—no toxicology tests, no ER findings consistent with poisoning, no physician diagnosis. This allegation is objectively false.

2. Physical Assault: Ms. Watson alleged Mr. Pigors physically assaulted her. Police records contain no reports, no witnesses, no photographs of injuries, and no criminal charges. This allegation is objectively false.

3. Threat to Lincoln: Ms. Watson alleged Mr. Pigors poses a threat to Lincoln. This allegation is directly contradicted by this Court's own July 17, 2024 order, which granted Mr. Pigors joint legal custody—a determination incompatible with finding him a threat to the child.

4. Drug Use/Hallucinations: Ms. Watson alleged Mr. Pigors uses drugs and experiences hallucinations. The HealthWest evaluation found no evidence of substance abuse or psychotic symptoms. This allegation is objectively false.

5. Stalking/Surveillance: Ms. Watson characterized normal co-parenting devices (home webcam, AirTag for locating belongings) as "stalking" and "surveillance." This mischaracterization of ordinary technology does not constitute evidence of danger.

These false allegations follow a troubling pattern: each escalates in severity, each emerges at strategic times in litigation, and none is corroborated by objective evidence.

F. Pattern of Parental Alienation and Gatekeeping

This is the THIRD instance of Ms. Watson withholding or suspending Mr. Pigors' parenting time:

1. March 28 - May 5, 2024: Ms. Watson unilaterally withheld Lincoln for 39 days before court proceedings were initiated.

2. October 20 - November 15, 2024: Ms. Watson again withheld Lincoln for 26 days without court authorization.

3. August 8, 2025 - Present: The current suspension has lasted 192+ days.

Total wrongful deprivation: THREE HUNDRED TWENTY-NINE (329) days—nearly eleven months of Lincoln's young life without his father.

Michigan law recognizes that gatekeeping and parental alienation harm children. MCL 722.23(c) (best interest factor includes "willingness and ability of each of the parties to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing parent-child relationship"); MCL 722.27a(8) (court must consider whether parent will allow parenting time in accordance with the order).

Despite this documented pattern, this Court has imposed NO sanctions against Ms. Watson for gatekeeping, but has sanctioned Mr. Pigors $250 for attempting to exercise his right to file motions.

G. Documented Harm to Lincoln

Lincoln is six years old. This is a critical period for:
• Identity formation and attachment security
• Understanding family relationships and family structure  
• Emotional regulation and trust development
• Social skills and relationship modeling

Complete separation from a previously involved parent during this critical period causes well-documented psychological harm:
• Attachment disruption and abandonment trauma
• Identity confusion regarding paternal relationship
• Increased risk of anxiety, depression, and behavioral problems
• Long-term difficulties in relationships and trust
• Parental alienation syndrome

Child development experts agree that harm from prolonged separation increases exponentially over time and becomes increasingly difficult to repair after 6+ months. Lincoln has already endured 192 days (6+ months) without his father. Each additional day deepens the harm.

III. LEGAL STANDARD

A. Standard for Ex Parte Relief Under MCR 3.207(B)

MCR 3.207(B) governs ex parte relief in domestic relations cases. The rule states:

"Ex parte relief may not be granted unless it clearly appears from specific facts shown by affidavit or by a verified pleading that immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage will result to the moving party before the adverse party or the adverse party's attorney can be heard in opposition."

This rule "must be strictly complied with." Grievance Administrator v. Fieger, 476 Mich 231, 244 (2006). "Substantial compliance" is insufficient. Id.

An ex parte order that fails to comply with the rule's requirements is void and must be set aside. Payne v. Payne, 172 Mich App 99 (1988).

B. Standard for Restricting Parenting Time Under MCL 722.27a

MCL 722.27a establishes a statutory presumption that parenting time "will not endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health." MCL 722.27a(1).

To overcome this presumption and deny or restrict parenting time, the party opposing parenting time must present "clear and convincing evidence" that parenting time would result in endangerment. MCL 722.27a(3).

"Clear and convincing evidence" is "evidence that produces in the mind of the trier of fact a firm belief or conviction as to the truth of the allegations sought to be established, evidence so clear, direct and weighty and convincing as to enable the fact-finder to come to a clear conviction, without hesitancy, of the truth of the precise facts in issue." In re Williams, 286 Mich App 253, 271 (2009).

This is the highest standard of proof in civil proceedings—higher than the "preponderance" standard and approaching the "beyond reasonable doubt" standard of criminal cases.

Additionally, the court must make specific written findings supporting any denial or restriction of parenting time. MCL 722.27a(3); MCR 3.210(D).

C. Standard for Protecting Constitutional Due Process

The parent-child relationship is a fundamental liberty interest protected by the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment. Troxel v. Granville, 530 US 57, 65 (2000); Stanley v. Illinois, 405 US 645, 651 (1972).

"The interest of parents in the care, custody, and control of their children ... is perhaps the oldest of the fundamental liberty interests recognized by this Court." Troxel, 530 US at 65.

Before the state may interfere with fundamental parental rights, procedural due process requires:
• Notice of the specific allegations
• Meaningful opportunity to be heard
• Right to present evidence and cross-examine adverse witnesses
• Impartial decision-maker
• Decision supported by findings based on appropriate burden of proof

Where parental rights are at stake, the Supreme Court has required "fundamentally fair procedures" and heightened reliability in fact-finding. Santosky v. Kramer, 455 US 745, 753-54 (1982).

IV. ARGUMENT

A. The August 8, 2025 Ex Parte Order Is Procedurally Void

The August 8, 2025 order suspending Mr. Pigors' parenting time fails to comply with MCR 3.207(B) and is void.

1. The Rule Requires Strict Compliance

MCR 3.207(B) requires ex parte relief to be supported by "specific facts shown by affidavit or by a verified pleading" demonstrating "immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage will result to the moving party before the adverse party or the adverse party's attorney can be heard in opposition."

Michigan courts require strict compliance with this rule. Grievance Administrator v. Fieger, 476 Mich at 244 ("Substantial compliance with a court rule is not enough; the rule must be strictly complied with."). This strict compliance requirement reflects the serious consequences of depriving parties of rights without notice—particularly where fundamental constitutional rights are at stake.

2. The August 8, 2025 Order Fails Every Element

The August 8, 2025 order fails each requirement of MCR 3.207(B):

a. No Verified Pleading or Affidavit

The record contains no verified pleading or affidavit supporting the August 8, 2025 order. Ms. Watson did not file a motion requesting suspension. No affidavit was submitted. No verification appears on any document.

The absence of a verified pleading or affidavit is not a technicality. Verification serves critical purposes: (1) it ensures the moving party has personal knowledge of the facts alleged; (2) it subjects the moving party to perjury prosecution for false statements; and (3) it provides the court and adverse party with a record of the specific factual basis for the order.

Without verification, there is no reliable factual basis for the order.

b. No Specific Facts Shown

The order does not identify what "specific facts" justified suspending parenting time without notice to Mr. Pigors. The order contains no findings explaining what immediate danger Lincoln faced. The order does not reference any specific incident, date, witness, or evidence.

MCR 3.207(B) requires "specific facts"—not generalized concerns, not unsubstantiated allegations, not suspicions. The absence of specific facts means Mr. Pigors cannot meaningfully respond to or rebut the basis for the order.

c. No Showing of Immediate and Irreparable Harm

The order does not explain what "immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage" would have resulted if Ms. Watson's concerns were heard on notice with Mr. Pigors present.

Mr. Pigors had been exercising parenting time under the July 17, 2024 order without incident. There is no evidence that scheduling a noticed hearing would have endangered Lincoln. Ms. Watson could have sought a hearing on shortened notice—even as soon as 24-48 hours—allowing the Court to hear both sides before entering an order.

The failure to demonstrate immediate harm that could not await a noticed hearing means the ex parte procedure was unnecessary and improperly invoked.

d. No Findings That Harm Would Result Before Notice Could Be Provided

The order contains no findings explaining why the matter could not be heard on notice before entering an order affecting Mr. Pigors' parental rights.

This element of MCR 3.207(B) is critical: it requires the movant to demonstrate not just that harm might occur, but that harm would occur in the time it would take to provide notice and hold a hearing. This is a high bar, reflecting the serious due process concerns with ex parte orders.

The record is silent on this element.

3. The Procedural Defects Are Not Harmless

These procedural defects are not harmless technicalities. They denied Mr. Pigors the most basic due process protections before depriving him of his fundamental constitutional right to parent his child.

• Mr. Pigors had no notice of what factual allegations he needed to rebut
• Mr. Pigors had no opportunity to present contrary evidence (HealthWest evaluation, medical records, police reports)
• Mr. Pigors had no opportunity to cross-examine Ms. Watson about her allegations
• Mr. Pigors had no opportunity to demonstrate the falsity of Ms. Watson's prior allegations

The Court cannot cure these defects retroactively by continuing the order at subsequent hearings, because each continuation compounds the harm.

4. The Proper Remedy Is to Vacate the Order

"An order issued in violation of [court rules] is void and must be set aside." Payne v. Payne, 172 Mich App 99, 102 (1988).

Where an ex parte order fails to comply with MCR 3.207(B), the order is void from inception. Setting it aside is not discretionary—it is required.

Upon vacating the August 8, 2025 order, Mr. Pigors' parenting time must revert to the schedule established in the last properly-entered order: the July 17, 2024 order providing 79 overnights per year.

B. The Suspension Violates Michigan's Statutory Presumption Favoring Parenting Time

Even if the August 8, 2025 order had been procedurally proper (which it was not), the 192-day suspension violates Michigan's statutory presumption in favor of parenting time.

1. MCL 722.27a Creates a Strong Presumption

MCL 722.27a establishes that "a child has a right to parenting time with a parent unless the court determines by clear and convincing evidence that parenting time would endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health."

This statutory presumption reflects Michigan's strong public policy favoring parent-child relationships. Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 890 (1994) ("the legislature has created a strong presumption in favor of granting parenting time").

The presumption cannot be overcome by speculation, unsubstantiated allegations, or preponderance of evidence. It requires "clear and convincing evidence" of actual endangerment—the highest civil burden of proof.

2. The Record Contains No Clear and Convincing Evidence

The record contains no clear and convincing evidence that resumption of Mr. Pigors' parenting time would endanger Lincoln:

• The HealthWest evaluation—the most comprehensive, objective evidence in the record—found NO basis to restrict parenting time and affirmatively recommended substantial time.

• Medical records contain NO evidence of injuries, abuse, or neglect during Mr. Pigors' parenting time.

• Police reports contain NO substantiated allegations of violence or danger.

• Ms. Watson's allegations have been repeatedly contradicted by objective evidence (e.g., no medical evidence of poisoning; no police reports of assault; HealthWest evaluation contradicting mental health allegations).

• This Court's own July 17, 2024 order granted Mr. Pigors joint legal custody—a finding incompatible with a determination that he poses a threat to Lincoln.

Clear and convincing evidence must be "so clear, direct and weighty and convincing as to enable the fact-finder to come to a clear conviction, without hesitancy." In re Williams, 286 Mich App at 271. The evidence here does not remotely approach this standard.

3. The Court Has Made No Written Findings

MCL 722.27a(3) and MCR 3.210(D) require the court to make specific written findings supporting any restriction of parenting time.

The August 8, 2025 order contains no findings. The continuations at subsequent hearings contain no findings. The record is devoid of any judicial explanation of:
• What specific evidence supports suspension
• Why that evidence constitutes "clear and convincing" proof
• What type of "endangerment" Lincoln would face
• What less restrictive alternatives were considered
• Why complete suspension (rather than supervised parenting time) is necessary

Written findings serve essential purposes: (1) they demonstrate the court applied the correct legal standard; (2) they allow appellate review; (3) they ensure the court carefully considered the evidence rather than acting on speculation or bias; and (4) they provide the parties with an explanation of the court's reasoning.

The absence of findings here is particularly troubling given the length of the suspension (192+ days) and the fundamental rights at stake.

4. The Suspension Exceeds Permissible Judicial Discretion

Even within the broad discretion granted to family courts, there are limits. A court abuses its discretion when it "violates a principle of law or makes findings of fact that are clearly against the great weight of the evidence." Dailey v. Kloenhamer, 291 Mich App 660, 664 (2011).

Suspending a parent's parenting time for 192+ days based on unsupported allegations, while ignoring objective evidence favoring the parent, and without making required findings, violates principles of law and is against the great weight of evidence.

C. The Suspension Violates Constitutional Due Process

The suspension of Mr. Pigors' parenting time without proper procedural protections violates his Fourteenth Amendment due process rights.

1. Parental Rights Are Fundamental Constitutional Rights

"The interest of parents in the care, custody, and control of their children ... is perhaps the oldest of the fundamental liberty interests recognized by this Court." Troxel v. Granville, 530 US at 65.

The Supreme Court has repeatedly held that the parent-child relationship is protected by the Due Process Clause. Stanley v. Illinois, 405 US at 651 ("The rights to conceive and to raise one's children have been deemed essential, basic civil rights of man."); Santosky v. Kramer, 455 US at 753 ("The fundamental liberty interest of natural parents in the care, custody, and management of their child does not evaporate simply because they have not been model parents.").

Mr. Pigors' relationship with Lincoln is not a privilege subject to discretionary state interference—it is a fundamental constitutional right.

2. Due Process Requires Fair Procedures Before Deprivation

Before the state may interfere with a fundamental right, the Constitution requires "fundamentally fair procedures." Santosky, 455 US at 754.

At minimum, due process in parenting time proceedings requires:
• Notice of the specific factual allegations
• Meaningful opportunity to be heard and present evidence
• Right to cross-examine adverse witnesses
• Impartial decision-maker
• Findings based on constitutionally adequate burden of proof

The August 8, 2025 order provided none of these protections. Mr. Pigors received no notice. He had no opportunity to be heard. He could not present evidence. He could not cross-examine Ms. Watson. No findings were made.

This is the paradigmatic due process violation: deprivation of a fundamental right without any procedural protections.

3. The 192-Day Deprivation Is Ongoing Violation

The due process violation is not limited to the moment the August 8, 2025 order was entered. It continues every day the suspension remains in effect without proper procedural protections.

Each continuation hearing without adequate findings, without opportunity to present evidence, and without application of the clear and convincing standard is a renewed violation of Mr. Pigors' constitutional rights.

The 192 days that have passed represent 192 days of unconstitutional deprivation of Mr. Pigors' fundamental parental rights.

4. The Reliance on Unauthenticated "Second Evaluation" Violates Due Process

Due process also requires that decisions affecting fundamental rights be based on reliable evidence. Santosky, 455 US at 767-68 (requiring "fundamentally fair procedures" and heightened reliability where parental rights at stake).

The Court's reliance on an alleged "second mental health evaluation" that has never been authenticated, never been introduced into evidence, never been testified to by an expert, and apparently was never completed violates due process principles of reliability.

Meanwhile, the Court excluded the authenticated, comprehensive HealthWest evaluation that Mr. Pigors completed at the Court's own direction. This selective admission of evidence—admitting unreliable evidence against Mr. Pigors while excluding reliable evidence in his favor—compounds the due process violation.

D. Immediate Restoration Is Required to Prevent Irreparable Harm

Emergency relief is warranted where there is ongoing irreparable harm that cannot be adequately remedied after-the-fact. Every additional day of separation causes such harm here.

1. The Legal Standard for Irreparable Harm

"Irreparable harm" exists where "the remedy at law is inadequate and where monetary damages cannot adequately compensate for the loss." Pontiac Fire Fighters Union Local 376 v. City of Pontiac, 482 Mich 1, 9 (2008).

The loss of the parent-child relationship cannot be compensated with money. "Makeup parenting time" cannot restore the developmental period Lincoln has already lost. The harm is, by definition, irreparable.

2. Child Development Science Establishes the Harm

Lincoln is six years old. Developmental psychology establishes this is a critical period for:
• Secure attachment formation
• Identity development, including understanding one's place in family structure
• Learning emotional regulation through relationship modeling
• Developing capacity for trust and healthy relationships

Prolonged separation from a parent during this period causes documented harm:
• Attachment disruption, creating lasting difficulties with relationships and trust
• Abandonment trauma and associated anxiety/depression
• Identity confusion about the missing parent
• Internalization of false narratives ("Dad is dangerous," "Dad abandoned me")
• Increased risk of behavioral and emotional problems

Child development experts agree that harm increases exponentially with length of separation. After 6+ months (the current duration), parent-child relationships become increasingly difficult to restore. The child may resist reunification, having adapted to the parent's absence. The child may have internalized alienating messages. The child may have formed attachment avoidance as a protective mechanism.

3. Each Additional Day Deepens the Harm

Lincoln has already lost 192 days with his father. Each additional day:
• Reinforces the message that father is dangerous or has abandoned him
• Deepens attachment disruption
• Makes eventual reunification more traumatic and difficult
• Increases the risk of permanent damage to the father-child relationship

Time is not neutral in child development. Each day of this critical period that passes without father-child contact is a day of development that occurs without that relationship—and that cannot be reclaimed.

4. This Court Has Authority and Obligation to Act Immediately

Courts have inherent authority to correct erroneous orders, particularly where constitutional rights are at stake and irreparable harm is ongoing. Mack v. Detroit, 467 Mich 186, 203 (2002).

This Court has both the authority and the obligation to immediately restore Mr. Pigors' parenting time to prevent further irreparable harm to Lincoln.

E. The Record Evidence Supports Immediate Restoration

The objective evidence in the record overwhelmingly supports immediate restoration of parenting time.

1. The HealthWest Evaluation

The HealthWest evaluation is the most comprehensive, reliable evidence in the record. It consisted of 82 pages of assessment, testing, clinical interviews, and expert analysis.

The evaluation found:
• Mr. Pigors does not pose danger to Lincoln
• Mr. Pigors has appropriate parenting skills
• No mental health concerns that would impair parenting
• Recommendation for substantial parenting time

This evaluation was court-ordered, conducted by qualified professionals, properly authenticated, and directly relevant to parenting time determination. It should be given substantial weight.

2. Medical Records Show No Harm

Lincoln's medical records contain no evidence of:
• Injuries during Mr. Pigors' parenting time
• Suspected abuse or neglect reported by medical providers
• Emergency room visits related to Mr. Pigors' care
• Any findings consistent with Ms. Watson's allegations

The absence of any medical evidence of harm is significant. If Mr. Pigors were truly dangerous to Lincoln, one would expect to find medical documentation over the years of their relationship.

3. Police Records Show No Criminal Conduct

Police reports contain no evidence of:
• Arrests or charges for domestic violence
• Substantiated allegations of assault
• Criminal stalking or harassment
• Any behavior that would endanger Lincoln

Again, the absence of police documentation is telling. Ms. Watson's allegations—if true—would constitute serious crimes requiring police investigation and prosecution.

4. Ms. Watson's Pattern of False Allegations

Ms. Watson has made multiple allegations that are objectively false or grossly exaggerated:
• Arsenic poisoning: Zero medical evidence
• Physical assault: Zero police documentation  
• Drug use/hallucinations: Contradicted by HealthWest evaluation
• Threat to child: Contradicted by Court's own custody order

This pattern of false allegations undermines Ms. Watson's credibility and cannot constitute clear and convincing evidence.

5. Mr. Pigors' Compliance With Court Orders

Mr. Pigors has complied with all court orders, including:
• The July 17, 2024 custody order
• Payment of child support
• Completion of court-ordered HealthWest evaluation
• Attendance at all scheduled hearings

This compliance demonstrates Mr. Pigors respects the legal process and can be trusted to follow a restored parenting time schedule.

F. Defendant's Pattern of Gatekeeping Warrants Immediate Relief

Ms. Watson's pattern of gatekeeping demonstrates the need for immediate court intervention.

1. Three Separate Instances of Withholding

This is the third time Ms. Watson has withheld or suspended Mr. Pigors' parenting time:
• March-May 2024: 39 days
• October-November 2024: 26 days
• August 2025-Present: 192+ days
• Total: 329 days (nearly 11 months)

This pattern is not coincidental. It demonstrates systematic gatekeeping designed to eliminate Mr. Pigors from Lincoln's life.

2. Gatekeeping Harms Children

Michigan law recognizes that gatekeeping harms children. MCL 722.23(c) includes as a best interest factor "the willingness and ability of each of the parties to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing parent-child relationship between the child and the other parent."

MCL 722.27a(8) requires the court to consider "whether a parent will allow parenting time in accordance with the order."

Research confirms that parental alienation and gatekeeping cause documented psychological harm to children, including increased rates of depression, anxiety, relationship difficulties, and identity problems.

3. The Court Has Not Sanctioned the Gatekeeping

Despite this documented pattern, this Court has imposed no sanctions against Ms. Watson. In fact, this Court stated it could not "hold it against her" because some of the withholding occurred before the custody case was filed.

This refusal to sanction gatekeeping sends the message that Ms. Watson can withhold parenting time without consequence. It incentivizes continued gatekeeping.

Meanwhile, Mr. Pigors has been sanctioned $250 for attempting to exercise his statutory right to file motions.

This disparate treatment—sanctioning the victim of gatekeeping while refusing to sanction the perpetrator—violates equal protection principles and Michigan's statutory framework protecting parenting time.

4. Immediate Restoration Is Necessary to Prevent Further Gatekeeping

Without immediate restoration and clear direction that further gatekeeping will result in serious sanctions (including potential custody modification), Ms. Watson has no incentive to facilitate Mr. Pigors' relationship with Lincoln.

The longer the suspension continues, the more difficult reunification becomes, and the more Ms. Watson can argue that disrupting Lincoln's "new normal" would be harmful. Immediate restoration is necessary to prevent Ms. Watson from benefiting from her own gatekeeping.

V. CONCLUSION AND RELIEF REQUESTED

For 192 consecutive days, six-year-old Lincoln has been completely deprived of contact with his father during a critical developmental period. This deprivation occurred without the procedural safeguards required by Michigan Court Rules, without the clear and convincing evidence required by Michigan statute, and without the due process protections required by the United States Constitution.

The August 8, 2025 ex parte order is procedurally void. The continued suspension violates MCL 722.27a's statutory presumption favoring parenting time. The entire process violates Mr. Pigors' fundamental constitutional rights.

Most importantly, every additional day of separation causes irreparable harm to Lincoln—harm that cannot be remedied with money or "makeup time" in the future.

The objective evidence overwhelmingly supports immediate restoration of parenting time. The HealthWest evaluation, medical records, and police records all contradict Ms. Watson's allegations. Ms. Watson's pattern of false allegations and systematic gatekeeping demonstrates the urgent need for judicial intervention.

WHEREFORE, Plaintiff Andrew J. Pigors respectfully requests that this Honorable Court:

A. IMMEDIATELY VACATE the August 8, 2025 ex parte order suspending parenting time;

B. RESTORE Plaintiff's parenting time to the schedule established in the July 17, 2024 order (79 overnights per year), effective immediately;

C. ORDER immediate placement of Lincoln with Plaintiff for makeup parenting time to begin the healing and reunification process;

D. SCHEDULE an evidentiary hearing within seven (7) days to determine appropriate makeup parenting time, potential custody modification, and sanctions;

E. ORDER Defendant to facilitate immediate resumption of parenting time without interference, obstruction, or negative messaging to Lincoln;

F. PROHIBIT Defendant from further unilateral suspension or withholding of parenting time;

G. AWARD Plaintiff such other and further relief as this Court deems just and equitable.


